content.description:
A classic endurance traverse. There are three cruxes, with the hardest arriving right at the end.

Your feet never stray more than 4 feet off the ground (and are sometimes just inches above the dirt).
Excellent hand jams and finger locks.  There's even a convenient jug for the exit moves.
content.protection: Easily bouldered...it would be tough to build an adequate TR anchor.

content.description: Tricky & sequential.  Perhaps the best route on the wall.  Drop your knee, lock off and REACH.
content.protection: Can be bouldered. Toprope with small to medium nuts and long slings.  It is also possible to use a rivet hanger or a small stopper to rig a hangerless bolt atop the route.

content.description: Last move crux highball boulder. Watch the last move or you'll fall and the landing is terrible.
content.protection: Crash pads it's a bit high
content.location: On the left face of mugu rock facing the ocean in the middle before the more deformed part, first hand in small crack

content.protection: Can be bouldered. Toprope from bolts.

content.description: An awkward wide section yields to solid finger locks.
content.protection: Can be bouldered. Toprope from bolts.

content.description: It's a highball v0 crux is midway through making an arm transition.
content.protection: Bring your crash pads it's about 20-25 feet
content.location: Move to the left face of mugu rock facing the ocean all the way to the right side exit to the arete start one hand in the circle other anywhere.

content.description: Climbs as an offwidth, easier as a layback to the right.
content.protection: Can be bouldered. Toprope with a small cam and bolts.

content.description: Sit down in the dirty crease under the short overhand on top of mugu rock. start with a sharp crimp for the right hand and a sloper just below for the left hand. Get a foot out on the crumbly overhung face and start working up the really nice but paint covered crimps.
content.location: Looking at the ocean, overhanging left corner of the cap boulder. If you climb up the scary 4th class dihedral on the left side (looking at ocean) you are right there.

content.description: One of the most popular and one of the best.  Follow the clean crack that zig-zags up the left side of the boulder.  Easier near the top, unless you choose the harder left-hand variation.
content.protection: Can be bouldered. Toprope with small to medium nuts and long slings.

content.description:
Follow fractured features up left side of Pt Mugu rock.

Use the sloping ledge to gain features or crack and work your way up.

Trending Â left is shorter and easier but loose.

Trending right is slightly longer and slightly harder
content.protection: Top rope from bolts using plenty of extension or build an anchor
content.location: Left most face of Pt Mugu rock. Left of the 5.9 arete.

content.description: Left hand on the arete, right hand in a two-finger pocket...hike your feet up and dyno to the sharp jug.  Goes with either hand.  5.7 climbing leads to the top.
content.protection: Can be bouldered.  Toprope with small to medium nuts and long slings.

content.description: Hard for the grade.  The crux is moving off of a painful fingerlock at mid-height.  The feet are bad almost the whole way.
content.protection: Can be bouldered. Toprope with small to medium nuts and long slings.
